Data Dictionary of 10 columns¶

  • price (Target Variable): price in US dollars (\$326--\$18,823)
  • carat : weight of the diamond (0.2--5.01)
  • cut : quality of the cut (Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium, Ideal)
  • color : diamond colour, from D (best) to J (worst)
  • clarity : a measurement of how clear the diamond is (I1 (worst), SI2, SI1, VS2, VS1, VVS2, VVS1, IF (best))
  • x : length in mm (0--10.74)
  • y : width in mm (0--58.9)
  • z : depth in mm (0--31.8)
  • depth : total depth percentage = z / mean(x, y) = 2 * z / (x + y) (43--79)
  • table : width of top of diamond relative to widest point (43--95)

In [22]:
# Function to plot categorical variables correlation plot
def cramers_corrected_stat(confusion_matrix):
    """ calculate Cramers V statistic for categorical-categorical association.
        uses correction from Bergsma and Wicher,
        Journal of the Korean Statistical Society 42 (2013): 323-328
    """
    chi2 = ss.chi2_contingency(confusion_matrix)[0]
    n = confusion_matrix.sum().sum()
    phi2 = chi2/n
    r,k = confusion_matrix.shape
    phi2corr = max(0, phi2 - ((k-1)*(r-1))/(n-1))   
    rcorr = r - ((r-1)**2)/(n-1)
    kcorr = k - ((k-1)**2)/(n-1)
    return np.sqrt(phi2corr / min( (kcorr-1), (rcorr-1)))
In [23]:
# Categorical Columns of diamonds data
print("Categorical Columns correlation of crashes data")

cols = ["cut", "color", "clarity"]
corrM = np.zeros((len(cols),len(cols)))

for col1, col2 in itertools.combinations(cols, 2):
    idx1, idx2 = cols.index(col1), cols.index(col2)
    corrM[idx1, idx2] = cramers_corrected_stat(pd.crosstab(diamonds_raw[col1], diamonds_raw[col2]))
    corrM[idx2, idx1] = corrM[idx1, idx2]

corr = pd.DataFrame(corrM, index=cols, columns=cols)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 12))
ax = sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, ax=ax); ax.set_title("Cramer V Correlation between Variables in diamonds");

Categorical Columns correlation of crashes data

Multiple Linear Regression¶

Prior assumption to consider for Multiple Linear Regression

If these assumptions are not fulfilled, then the algorithm will not predict an accurate output.

  • No multi-collinearity should exist
  • No correlation between residuals
  • There are no pattern in the residual (should be random)
  • Residual should be normally distributed (skewness should be low)

Random Forest Regressor¶

Prior assumption to consider for Random Forest

  • Non-parametric and can thus handle skewed and multi-modal data
  • High potential to overfit datasets that are particularly noisy
  • Biased towards categorical predictors
In [55]:
RR = RandomForestRegressor()
RR_fit = RR.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_RFR = RR.predict(X_test)
In [56]:

RR R score predict on train data: 0.9186463113331425
RR r2 score on test data: 0.9830067696178724

Evaluation of the model¶

  • R-Sqaure and Adjusted R-Square: how much variation a target value has against the features)
  • Mean Squared Error (MSE): an average of the sum of the square of residuals
  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE): an average of the sum of the absolute distance of residuals
  • Ploting Predicted Values Vs Actual Values
  • Ploting Predicted Values Vs Residual Values
  • Plotting the distribution of residuals
In [78]:
R2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_LR)
n = X_test.shape[0]
p = X_test.shape[1] - 1
adj_rsquared = 1-(1-R2)*((n-1)/(n-p-1))

# Predicted Values Vs Residual Values

plt.xlabel('Predicted prices')
plt.ylabel('Residuals', fontsize=14)
plt.title('1(b) Residuals vs Fitted Values')

plt.xlabel('Residuals')

plt.show()
